[[File:Leftsidedcerebellarstroke.PNG|thumb|Left sided cerebellar stroke due to occlusion of a vertebral artery]]
'''Cerebellar stroke syndrome''' is a condition in which the circulation to the [[cerebellum]] is impaired due to a [[lesion]] of the [[superior cerebellar artery]], [[anterior inferior cerebellar artery]] or the [[posterior inferior cerebellar artery]].<ref name="UrbanWicht2001">{{cite journal |last1= Urban |first1= P.P. |last2= Wicht |first2= S. |last3= Vukurevic |first3=G. |last4= Fitzek |first4= C. |last5= Fitzek |first5= S. |last6= Stoeter |first6= P. |last7= Massinger |first7= C. |last8= Hopf |first8= H.C. |displayauthors= 4 |title=Dysarthria in acute ischemic stroke: Lesion topography, clinicoradiologic correlation, and etiology |journal= [[Neurology (journal)|Neurology]] |volume= 56 |issue= 8 |year= 2001 |pages= 1021–7 |pmid= 11320172 |doi= 10.1212/WNL.56.8.1021}}</ref>

Cardinal signs include [[Vertigo (medical)|vertigo]], [[headache]], [[vomiting]], and [[ataxia]].<ref name="StrokeSyndromes">{{cite book |last1= Caplan |first1= Louis R. |last2= Bogousslavsky |first2= Julien |title= Stroke Syndromes |publisher= [[Cambridge University Press]] |year= 2001 |pages= |isbn=0521771420 |ref= {{sfnref|Caplan & Bogousslavsky|2001}}}}{{page needed|date=July 2014}}</ref>

Cerebellar strokes account for only 2-3% of the 600,000 strokes that occur each year in the United States.<ref name="KellyStein2001">{{cite journal |last1= Kelly |first1= P.J. |last2= Stein |first2= J. |last3= Shafqat |first3= S. |last4= Eskey |first4= C. |last5= Doherty |first5= D. |last6= Chang |first6= Y. |last7= Kurina |first7= A. |last8= Furie |first8= K.L. |displayauthors= 4 |title= Functional recovery after rehabilitation for cerebellar stroke |url= http://stroke.ahajournals.org/content/32/2/530.long |journal= [[Stroke (journal)|Stroke]] |volume= 32 |issue= 2 |year= 2001 |pages= 530–4 |pmid= 11157193 |doi= 10.1161/01.STR.32.2.530}}</ref> They are far less common than strokes which occur in the [[cerebral hemispheres]]. In recent years [[mortality rates]] have decreased due to advancements in health care which include earlier [[diagnosis]] through [[MRI]] and [[CT scanning]].<ref name="jensen"/> Advancements have also been made which allow earlier management for common complications of cerebellar stroke such as [[brainstem]] compression and [[hydrocephalus]].<ref name="jensen">{{cite journal |last1= Jensen |first1= M.B. |last2= St. Louis |first2= E.K. |title= Management of acute cerebellar stroke |journal= [[JAMA Neurology|Archives of Neurology]] |volume= 62 |issue= 4 |year= 2005 |pages= 537–44 |url= http://archneur.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=788140 |doi= 10.1001/archneur.62.4.537 |pmid= 15824250}}</ref>

Research is still needed in the area of cerebellar stroke management; however, several factors may lead to poor outcomes in individuals who have a cerebellar stroke. These factors include:
# Declining levels of [[consciousness]]
# New signs of [[brainstem]] involvement
# Progressing [[Hydrocephalus]]
# Stroke to the midline of the cerebellum (a.k.a. the [[vermis]]) <ref name="jensen"/>

