'''Eddie Bennett''' (1904 &ndash; January 16, 1935) was an American [[batboy]] and [[mascot]] for several teams, most notably the [[New York Yankees]] during the 1920s and 1930s. At the time of his death, Bennett was considered to be the "most famous mascot in the world".<ref name="obit">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=IN9BAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-qkMAAAAIBAJ&pg=5200,5375809&dq=eddie+bennett&hl=en|title=Smiling Eddie Bennett Mascot Who Helped Yankees To Three World Series Dead|last=Associated Press|date=January 18, 1935|work=The Telegraph Herald and Times-Journal|page=8|accessdate=22 April 2012}}</ref>
==Early life== Bennett was born in [[Flatbush, Brooklyn]]. When Bennett was very young, he received a spine injury suffered in a [[baby carriage]] incident.<ref name="book">{{cite book|last=Frommer|first=Harvey|title=Five O'Clock Lightning: Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, And The Greatest Baseball Team in History, The 1927 New York Yankees|year=2008|publisher=Wiley Publishing|location=Hoboken, New Jersey|isbn=9780471778127|page=196|ref=Frommer}}<!--|accessdate=April 22, 2012--></ref> That injury left Bennett with a [[hunchback]]ed back and restricted his growth, by the time he was an adult he was considered a dwarf.<ref name="book"/> Bennett's parents died in the [[1918 flu epidemic]], and Bennett, needing a job, convinced [[Chicago White Sox]] outfielder [[Happy Felsch]] that he had "mystical powers" that could bring good luck to everyone that uses him.<ref name="obit"/> He became Felsch's personal mascot and when Felsch play improved, he moved on to become the White Sox personal mascot in 1919.<ref name="obit"/> The club won the pennant that year with Bennett sitting on the bench with the players. During the [[1919 World Series]], eight members of the White Sox, including Felsch decided to [[Black Sox scandal|throw the World Series]]. A scandal erupted which later led those eight players receiving lifetime bans from baseball and Bennett left the team to join his hometown [[History of the Brooklyn Dodgers|Brooklyn Robins]].<ref name="obit"/> The Robins won the pennant in [[1920 Brooklyn Robins season|1920]], but after participating in the <ref>{{cite web|last=Morris|first=Peter|title=Eddie Bennett|url=http://sabr.org/bioproj/person/40572eaa|accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> first three [[1920 World Series|World Series]] games both the second and third being Robins victories, Bennett wasn't invited to join the team at [[1920 Cleveland Indians season|Cleveland]].<ref name="seldom">{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=5tImAAAAIBAJ&sjid=hgIGAAAAIBAJ&pg=2544,5221437&dq=eddie-bennett&hl=en|title=Mascots Seldom Stays in Baseball|last=Associated Press|date=February 14, 1932|work=The Sunday Morning Star|accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref> The Robins went on to lose their next four games, and the series to the Indians. He soon left the team citing "lack of trust".<ref name="obit"/>
==New York Yankees== At the age of 18, Bennett became the bat boy for the New York Yankees on the request of Yankees owner [[Jacob Ruppert]]. He was considered to be a "good luck charm" by the members of the club, and became a well-known celebrity in New York.{{sfn|Frommer|2008|p=57|ps=none}} Each year, he went down to Florida to join the Yankees [[spring training]].<ref name="seldom"/> He became one of [[Babe Ruth]]'s closest friends on the team, and they played catch on the field nearly every game. A close confidant of manager [[Miller Huggins]], Bennett usually sat next to Huggins during Yankees games, pointing out issues he noticed on the field, a predecessor of a [[bench coach]] in today's baseball.{{sfn|Frommer|2008|p=69|ps=none}}
==Decline and death== On May 19, 1932, Bennett was hit by a taxi on a New York City street. He suffered a broken leg and other injuries from which he never recovered. To find relief from the pain he suffered from the injuries, Bennett started to abuse alcohol.<ref name="book"/> He was forced to retire as the Yankees mascot in the middle of 1933 season, although Ruppert insisted he remain on the payroll all year. ''The New York Times'' reported that the "notoriously superstitious" ballplayers and fans blamed Bennett's absence on the Yankees' failure to win the pennant in 1933 and 1934.<ref name="tokens">{{cite news|title=Yankees' Mascot Dies Amid Tokens; Eddie Bennett Found in Room Surrounded by Baseballs, Bats and Players' Photos.|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1935/01/17/93666674.html?pageNumber=42|accessdate=August 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=January 17, 1935|page=42|language=en}}</ref>
In January 1935, Bennett died penniless in his room at a lodging house at 115 W. 84th Street in Manhattan, age 31. The coroner ruled the cause of death as alcoholism; according to his landlady, Bennett had told her that drinking was the only relief from his chronic pain.<ref name="tokens"/> He had no known relatives and had been scheduled to be buried in a [[pauper's grave]] until Ruppert paid for his funeral and burial.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yankees to Bury Mascot; Club Officials to Attend Funeral Tomorrow for Eddie Bennett |url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1935/01/18/93442094.html?pageNumber=25|accessdate=13 August 2017|work=The New York Times|date=January 18, 1935|page=25|language=en}}</ref> Ruppert and general manager [[Ed Barrow]] were not able to attend the service but sent flowers. The entire Yankee front office staff of [[Paul Krichell]], [[Gene McCann]], Mark Roth, George Perry, and Charlie McManus accompanied Bennett's body from the funeral parlor to [[St. Gregory the Great Church (Manhattan)|St. Gregory the Great Church]] for the service and on to [[St. John Cemetery (Queens)|St. John's Cemetery]] in Queens for burial.<ref>{{cite news|title=Funeral Services for Eddie Bennett – Floral Tributes to Memory of Baseball Mascot Sent by Ruppert and Others|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1935/01/20/93442577.html?pageNumber=32|accessdate=August 13, 2017|work=The New York Times|date=January 20, 1935|page=32|language=en}}</ref> No player attended the service despite being it being the off-season.{{sfn|Frommer|2008|p=197|ps=none}}
==Legacy==
Bennett's life was mentioned by billionaire [[Warren Buffett]] during his annual stockholder report in 2002, saying that Bennett was a key role model during Buffett's career in investing, naming him a "winner at every costs".{{sfn|Frommer|2008|p=197|ps=none}}
