'''Harvey Julien Feldman''' (June 25, 1931 – February 24, 2009)<ref>[http://www.adst.org/OH%20TOCs/Feldman,%20Harvey.toc.pdf The Association for Diplomatic Studies and Training Foreign Affairs Oral History Project: HARVEY FELDMAN]</ref> was a diplomat of the [[United States]], best known for planning the [[1972 Nixon visit to China]].<ref name="WaPo">{{citation|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/03/08/AR2009030801657.html|periodical=The Washington Post|date=2009-03-08|accessdate=2009-08-19|title=Obituaries: Harvey J. Feldman, 77 – Ambassador Helped Plan Nixon's China Visit|last=Bernstein|first=Adam}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Feldman was born in [[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]], New York. He attended the [[University of Chicago]] as both an undergraduate and a master's student in Chinese studies, receiving his M.A. in 1954.<ref name="WaPo"/> While still a student in 1952, he married his first wife, Carolina (Carol) Borja Feldman, a classmate at the University of Chicago.<ref>{{citation|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/chicagotribune/access/500583662.html?dids=500583662:500583662&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Jun+11%2C+1952&author=&pub=Chicago+Tribune&desc=Paths+of+Campus+Romance+Leading+to+Altar+for+Many+at+N.+U.+and+U.+of+Chicago&pqatl=google|date=1952-06-11|accessdate=2011-06-13|title=Paths of Campus Romance Leading to Altar for Many at NU and U. of Chicago|last=Moss|first=Ruth|periodical=Chicago Tribune}}</ref> Their marriage ended in divorce.<ref name="WaPo"/> After their divorce, she died in 1981.{{Citation needed|date=October 2009}} He married his second wife Laura Sherman in 1976.<ref name="WaPo"/>

==Career==
Feldman served in [[Hong Kong]] for eight years, Taiwan for six, and Japan for four years. As a member of the Policy Planning Staff of the [[United States Department of State|State Department]], he helped plan U.S. president [[Richard Nixon]]'s first [[1972 Nixon visit to China|visit to China in 1972]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.uscc.gov/bios/04_02_06bios/feldmanharvey%20.htm|publisher=United States–China Economic and Security Review Commission|title=Ambassador Harvey Feldman: Senior Fellow in China Policy, Asian Studies Center|date=2004-02-06|accessdate=2009-08-19|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090807001020/http://www.uscc.gov/bios/04_02_06bios/feldmanharvey%20.htm|archivedate=2009-08-07|df=}}</ref> He continued involvement with the process of relations with China when he became the Director of the Office of Republic of China Affairs in September 1977. In that capacity, he and Lee Marks began to draft the [[Taiwan Relations Act]] at the request of [[Richard Holbrooke]]; the act would be passed into law in 1979. He also created the [[American Institute in Taiwan]] which replaced the U.S. embassy in Taipei after relations were shifted to Beijing.<ref>{{citation|periodical=Taipei Times|url=http://www.taipeitimes.com/News/taiwan/archives/2003/04/09/201379|date=2003-04-09|accessdate=2009-08-19|title=Penning the future of Taiwan|last=Snyder|first=Charles}}</ref> On August 2, 1979, he was appointed to the position of U.S. ambassador to [[Papua New Guinea]] and the [[Solomon Islands]], resident in [[Port Moresby]], the capital of PNG; he held that position until May 25, 1981.<ref>{{citation|url=https://history.state.gov/departmenthistory/people/feldman-harvey-j|publisher=Office of the Historian, Department of State|location=United States|title=Harvey J. Feldman|accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> He later served as an alternative [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations|U.S. representative to]] the [[United Nations]], an ambassadorial-rank position and his final role in the State Department. He retired in 1986.<ref name="WaPo"/>

==Retirement and death==
After his retirement, Feldman continued his involvement with China affairs. In 1989, he met with then-[[President of the Republic of China|ROC president]] [[Lee Teng-hui]] and advised him on potential strategies for helping the ROC to [[China and the United Nations|regain membership in the United Nations]].<ref name="ChinaPost">{{citation|url=http://www.chinapost.com.tw/taiwan/2007/09/07/121499/Former-United.htm|periodical=The ChinaPost|date=2007-09-07|accessdate=2009-08-19|title=Former U.S. official criticizes National Security Council for not recognizing Taiwan|last=Che|first=Stephen}}</ref> In 1994, he became a fellow in China Policy of [[The Heritage Foundation]], a conservative think tank.<ref name="WaPo"/> In 2007, he spoke out against remarks by [[United States National Security Council]] Senior Director for Asian Affairs Dennis Wilder stating that "Taiwan, or the Republic of China, is not at this point a state in the international community"; Feldman responded that U.S. government had no basis under law to oppose ROC membership in international bodies.<ref name="ChinaPost"/>

Outside of his China-related activities, Feldman was also a board member of the [[Jewish Institute for National Security Affairs]] and a partner in consultancy firm Global Business Access.<ref name="WaPo"/> He died on February 24, 2009 at the age of 77 due to complications from [[aortic dissection]]. He was survived by two sons from his marriage to Carol Borja Feldman (Chris Feldman and Peter Feldman), as well as his second wife Laura Sherman and their son Alex Feldman, as well as a sister, three grandchildren, and two great-granddaughters.<ref name="WaPo"/>

