{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}} {{Infobox film | name = How to Die in Oregon | image = How to Die in Oregon FilmPoster.jpeg | image_size = 220px | border = yes | alt = | caption = Poster | director = [[Peter Betty (filmmaker)|Peter Richardson]] | producer = Peter Betty | starring = Cody Curtis | music = [[Max Richter]] | distributor = [[Clearcut Productions]] | released = {{Film date|2011|1|23|[[27th Sundance Film Festival|Sundance]]}} | runtime = 107 minutes | country = United States | language = English | budget = $750,000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/01/25/movies/25sundance.html | title= Unflinching End-of-Life Moments | last=Barnes | first=Brook | publisher=[[The New York Times]]|date=2011-01-24|accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref> }} '''''How to Die in Oregon''''' is a 2011 American [[documentary film]] produced and directed by [[Peter Richardson (filmmaker)|Peter Richardson]]. It is set in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Oregon]] and covers the state's [[Oregon Death with Dignity Act|Death with Dignity Act]] that allows terminally ill patients to self-administer barbiturates prescribed by their physician to end their own life, referred to as [[assisted suicide]] to opponents and [[medical aid in dying]] to proponents.
==Release== The film was released in January 2011 at the [[27th Sundance Film Festival]] and began airing on [[HBO]] later in the year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/01/28/us-film-oregon-idUSTRE70R15420110128|title=HBO documentary probes Oregon's euthanasia law|author=Lowe, Justin|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=2011-01-28|accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref> Peter Richardson, a native Oregonian, got the idea to produce the film as the state's law was upheld by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] in the 2006 case [[Gonzales v. Oregon]].
==Critical reception== ''How to Die in Oregon'' was well received by critics, currently holding a 100% "fresh" rating on [[Rotten Tomatoes]] based on 8 reviews.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/how_to_die_in_oregon/ | title=How to Die in Oregon | publisher=Rotten Tomatoes | accessdate=May 9, 2014}}</ref>
The film won the Grand Jury Prize for Documentaries at the [[27th Sundance Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/madaboutmovies/2011/01/how_to_die_in_oregon_takes_top.html|title='How to Die in Oregon' takes top documentary prize at Sundance|author=Levy, Shawn|publisher=[[The Oregonian]]|date=2011-01-29|accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eonline.com/uberblog/b223267_sundance_goes_wild_like_crazy_how_die.html|title=Sundance Goes Wild for Like Crazy; How to Die in Oregon Nabs Top Honors|author=Fowler, Brandi|publisher=[[E! Online]]|date=2011-01-29|accessdate=2011-01-30}}</ref>
